use of physical structures. By the 1960s, however, the built environment of the border began to display increasingly obvious systemic flaws. More often than not, Alvarez shows, federal agencies in both countries responded with more construction—“compensatory building” designed to mitigate unsustainable policies relating to immigration, black markets, and the natural world. Border Land, Border Water reframes our understanding of how the border has come to look and function as it does and is essential to current debates about the future of the US-Mexico divide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBuildingzMexican-American Border Region. 0aPublic worksxPolitical aspectszMexican-American Border RegionxHistory. 0aWaterworkszMexican-American Border RegionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31900040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477319024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477319024/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK